 p2: 'relentless pressure it brings. But it\u2019s on the rise around the world as firms look to become more efficient annual revenue used “non-traditional” monitoring techniques on staff last year. and interacting, which can be good for both the firm and employees themselves. A growing number of analytics companies offer this service. They gather “data exhaust” left by employees\u2019 email and instant radio-frequency microphones. These can check how much time you spend talking, your volume and tone of voice, even if protect employees against bullying and sexual harassment. of this it was that people who sat at 12-person lunch tables tended to interact, share ideas more and outperform those who regularly sat at four-person tables, a fact that would probably have gone undetected without such data analysis. Over the last few years a Stockholm co-working space called Epicenter has gone much further and holds popular “chipping parties”, where people can have microchips implanted in their hands. They can use the implants to access electronically-controlled doors, or monitor how typing speed correlates with biometrics to such devices. As long as such schemes are voluntary, there will probably be a growing number of convenience- oriented uses so that a substantial number of workers would opt to have a chip inserted. But if implanted chips are used to reduce slack time or rest breaks, that could prove to be detrimental. And if surveillance monitoring initiatives are communicated and this could prevent possible revolts being staged. If bosses don\u2019t communicate effectively, employees assume the worst. But if they\u2019re open about the information they\u2019re collecting and what they\u2019re doing with it, research suggests 46% of employees are generally okay with it. Although many such monitoring schemes use anonymised data and participation is voluntary, many staffers remain sceptical and fear an erosion of their civil liberties. unpopular tool of oppression that proves counterproductive.',
